Histologic evaluation showed atypical stromal cells, which support the diagnosis of sarcoma. None of the other options suggest a diagnosis of a juvenile granulosa cell tumor.

The nodules protruding from the vaginal canal with the appearance of "a bunch of grapes" and the presence of atypical stromal cells positive for polyclonal desmin suggest a diagnosis of sarcoma. Adenocarcinoma and SCC are malignant epithelial tumors and verrucous carcinoma is a subtype of SCC that typically arises in the oral cavity, not in the vaginal canal.
